03922nam a22005535i 9780822395768DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223957687 a10.1515/97808223957682doi  a(DE-B1597)552923  a(OCoLC)809910888  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aRC279.B55bL58 2012 7aMED0780002bisacsh04a362.196a362.196/99400968831 aLivingston, Julie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImprovising Medicine :bAn African Oncology Ward in an Emerging Cancer Epidemic /cJulie Livingston. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (246 p.) :b13 photographs, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tOne. The Other Cancer Ward -- tTwo. Neoplastic Africa. Mapping Circuits of Toxicity and Knowledge -- tThree. Creating and Embedding Cancer in Botswana's Oncology Ward -- tInterlude. Amputation Day at Princess Marina Hospital -- tFour. The Moral Intimacies of Care -- tFive. Pain and Laughter -- tSix. After ARVs, During Cancer, Before Death -- tEpilogue. Changing Wards, Further Improvisations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Improvising Medicine, Julie Livingston tells the story of Botswana's only dedicated cancer ward, located in its capital city of Gaborone. This affecting ethnography follows patients, their relatives, and ward staff as a cancer epidemic emerged in Botswana. The epidemic is part of an ongoing surge in cancers across the global south; the stories of Botswana's oncology ward dramatize the human stakes and intellectual and institutional challenges of an epidemic that will shape the future of global health. They convey the contingencies of high-tech medicine in a hospital where vital machines are often broken, drugs go in and out of stock, and bed-space is always at a premium. They also reveal cancer as something that happens between people. Serious illness, care, pain, disfigurement, and even death emerge as deeply social experiences. Livingston describes the cancer ward in terms of the bureaucracy, vulnerability, power, biomedical science, mortality, and hope that shape contemporary experience in southern Africa. Her ethnography is a profound reflection on the social orchestration of hope and futility in an African hospital, the politics and economics of healthcare in Africa, and palliation and disfigurement across the global south.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aCancerxTreatmentzBotswana. 0aCancerzBotswana. 0aOncologyzBotswana. 7aMEDICAL / Public Health.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395768zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395768423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395768.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles